    <div class="section firstReview">
      

<div id="review_3514090867" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3514090867" />
    <a title="Deb~Books &#39;n Tea" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/25849610-deb-books-n-tea"><img alt="Deb~Books &#39;n Tea" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1634827121p2/25849610.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3514090867?book_show_action=true">Dec 03, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Deb~Books &#39;n Tea" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Deb~Books &#39;n Tea" href="/user/show/25849610-deb-books-n-tea">Deb~Books &#39;n Tea</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3514090867" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer216039282203509280">Butterfly Tears is a book with a collection of 15 fantastic short stories all written by Zoe S. Roe. I loved all of the stories in this book. There is somewhat of a loosely common theme throughout regarding Chinese women who start out living in China, and who have experienced the Revolution under Mao Tse-tung and then the changes that occurred when he died. Most of the women immigrated from China to Canada and a few to the United States to start a new life and to experience freedom and the new c</span>
  <span id="freeText216039282203509280" style="display:none">Butterfly Tears is a book with a collection of 15 fantastic short stories all written by Zoe S. Roe. I loved all of the stories in this book. There is somewhat of a loosely common theme throughout regarding Chinese women who start out living in China, and who have experienced the Revolution under Mao Tse-tung and then the changes that occurred when he died. Most of the women immigrated from China to Canada and a few to the United States to start a new life and to experience freedom and the new culture available to them. There is also an underlying theme of feminism as there are some women who had found themselves in difficult situations such as abuse, betrayal or lost love and learned that they are actually strong enough to be able to live a life on their own in Canada/US and make their own choices, including dating. One part I like is where there is progress and opportunity for the women to discover that they can actually go to work, college and earn education and make a life, a living and choices for themselves, where they couldn't before. I like the strength the women grow into for themselves in the stories. I liked the stand up gentlemen with morals in the stories too. (and I did not like the men who were horrible jerks!) <br /><br />Roe does a terrific job of bringing her characters in each story to life. You can feel their feelings and experience how their life is where they are living and who they are influenced by in their timely surroundings. The supporting characters in the stories are also portrayed wonderfully and play a big part in the success of each storyline as well. <br /><br />The 15 Stories were: <br /><br />Butterfly Tears*<br />Wild Onions*<br />Yearning<br />Frog Fishing<br />A Woman Of China<br />Ten Yuan<br />Balloons*<br />Twin Rivers<br />Herbs*<br />A Mandarin Duck<br />Noodles<br />Gingko<br />Fortune-Telling<br />Life Insurance*  (loved!)<br />Jing and the Caterpillar <br /><br />(*=My favorite stories)<br /><br />I enjoyed this book and if you like stories about strong women, and women who have made the choice to immigrate from China to Canada or the United States to begin a new life of freedom, you will too. <br /><br />I would like to thank the author, Zoe S. Roe for a complementary digital copy of this book I received in exchange for an honest review. All opinions are my own.</span>
  <a data-text-id="216039282203509280" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


