<div id="review_3805357718" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3805357718" />
    <a title="Louanne" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/128413775-louanne"><img alt="Louanne" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3805357718?book_show_action=true">Feb 03, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Louanne" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Louanne" href="/user/show/128413775-louanne">Louanne</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/128413775-louanne?shelf=lu">lu</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3805357718" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17954103667068432671">&quot;Butterfly tears&quot; published by Inanna Poetry and fiction series, written by Zoé S. Roy, writer with Chinese roots, has fascinated us through fifteen short stories of the lives of heroes living in China, in a troubled time under the Cultural Revolution of Mao.<br/><br/>I enjoyed these fifteen dramas that open on tragic subjects such as the indoctrination of young adolescents to free will alienated from the cause, enslaved to Chinese communist and totalitarian ideology after 1966, which set off a wave of de</span>
  <span id="freeText17954103667068432671" style="display:none">"Butterfly tears" published by Inanna Poetry and fiction series, written by Zoé S. Roy, writer with Chinese roots, has fascinated us through fifteen short stories of the lives of heroes living in China, in a troubled time under the Cultural Revolution of Mao.<br /><br />I enjoyed these fifteen dramas that open on tragic subjects such as the indoctrination of young adolescents to free will alienated from the cause, enslaved to Chinese communist and totalitarian ideology after 1966, which set off a wave of denunciations, suicides and 50 million deaths ...<br /><br />The narration is fluid, lively and calls out to the reader who is, for his part, the antipodes of life lived in China. We learn the fate of the victims of the subversive regime advocating non-ambition and manipulation of young people.<br />These are fifteen mini-novels that reveal a plurality of facets of the Cultural Revolution so little known in the West, and the cleavages of this country torn in its very heart, which is losing its soul. His stolen youth is recruited by the Red Guards! Yet the youth is the jewel of any homeland, its essence and its power and Mao understood it well, just like Hitler with his Hitler youth.<br /><br />The dogmatic myth of the Chinese Orthodoxy which was once Stalin's advocate, in 1950, who turned his jacket over, during his poignant stories, where these women mourn their families, their former countries, their belonging to their roots lost under the yoke of Mao.<br /><br />A deep unwavering sadness invaded me as I read it, faced with the cruelty and despotism of the male gender in certain stories ... Faced with this image of the super Father of the nation, who has the right to life over anyone, to the image of this communist emperor.<br /><br />The Chinese woman retains a deep dignity and exemplary courage here, and Zoé S Roy generously shares with us these fifteen stories from her country of birth. However, it is about the inherent pride and dignity of their nation, which has been trampled on in favor of Communist pragmatism, if I understood correctly.<br /><br />The sets and characters are admirably well set up, and participate, crescendo, in the horror of certain situations sometimes. The sentences arise in the middle of the text, intensifying the feeling felt, and overwhelming the reader, mixing with the inner word and the spoken words. A pure treat.<br /><br />A vibrant tribute to the transcendental value of Chinese women plunged into the heart of human tragedies caused by Mao. She never abandons her convictions inherited from several generations, and this despite the icon stigmatized by the repressive leader of the Middle Kingdom.<br /><br />Caught up in these little novels, I never let go and I admired the disconcerting simplicity of these words, in a time that was burning and painful for these people caught in the grip of their violent sovereign.<br /> <br />This is all the magic of these stories that immortalize the soul of these wonderful women, fighting in their ways, their nobility and their integrity, which shapes this book.<br />A duty of memory and respect, I perceived, that the writer majestically staged, and which troubled me.<br /><br />I would be tempted to add that each story could be developed and contain a full book.<br /><br />A big Bravo! How can we forget the lives of these heroines, these parents of those who now rule the richest country on the planet, who lived this suspended and silent terror, oppressed, who are the great strength of this book on this unbearable subject, built like fifteen ample autobiographies - which I love - and this despite their brevity.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17954103667068432671" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


