<div id="review_3838030206" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3838030206" />
    <a title="Donna Frederick" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/129011100-donna-frederick"><img alt="Donna Frederick" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3838030206?book_show_action=true">Feb 14, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Donna Frederick" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Donna Frederick" href="/user/show/129011100-donna-frederick">Donna Frederick</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3838030206" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer109249395237310181">Butterfly Tears is a collection of emotionally evocative stories that are snapshots of the lives of Chinese women set in China, Canada, and the U.S. from the 1960s through to the early 2000s. <br/><br/>While all non-Indigenous Canadians and Americans have a family history of immigration, it is sometimes difficult for those born in the new country to connect with the experience of their immigrant ancestors. This collection of stories offers the unusual opportunity to peer into the lives of young women who </span>
  <span id="freeText109249395237310181" style="display:none">Butterfly Tears is a collection of emotionally evocative stories that are snapshots of the lives of Chinese women set in China, Canada, and the U.S. from the 1960s through to the early 2000s. <br /><br />While all non-Indigenous Canadians and Americans have a family history of immigration, it is sometimes difficult for those born in the new country to connect with the experience of their immigrant ancestors. This collection of stories offers the unusual opportunity to peer into the lives of young women who made a courageous journey to a new home. These young women are often filled with hope for the opportunities available to Canadian women but also repulsed by their new practical reality which contains things like raw vegetable and lettuce salads and disconcerting Halloween costumes. Some of the stories evoke a sense of fondness for the lost world of the characters' childhoods which is mixed with fear and frustrations created by the reality of the Maoist dictatorship. Others portray a reality of longing and loneliness wherein the women long to hear their mother tongue being spoken and the sound of traditional Chinese music. The stories also carry some feminist themes in that they demonstrate how life in both China and Canada can hold physical, sexual, and emotional dangers for women. <br /><br />Some of these stories are profoundly sad. The pain and traumatic memories of the characters are haunting. Yet, none of the sufferings is gratuitous or sensationalized. While some of the characters act out, most suffer from a sort of quiet, introverted longing. Readers may come away feeling that even though fiction, the stories reflect true life experiences that need to be revealed and known by the children and grandchildren of those women who are represented by the characters. These are stories that true-life mothers and grandmothers would never tell because they are too personal and yet they are stories that must be told.<br /><br />Butterfly Tears, because it contains violence, adult situations, and other potentially upsetting content is likely not a book for younger readers. However, this book will be interesting to those who are the children of Asian immigrants to North America, anyone interested in feminist literature, and women in general. While the stories are sometimes difficult to read from an emotional point of view, the book is highly recommended reading<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="109249395237310181" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


