<div id="review_3673989807" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3673989807" />
    <a title="Michelle" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/39210991-michelle"><img alt="Michelle" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1592003579p2/39210991.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3673989807?book_show_action=true">Dec 09, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michelle" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michelle" href="/user/show/39210991-michelle">Michelle</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3673989807" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9136876604242912942">Butterfly Tears is a lovely collection of short stories by Canadian author, Zoe Roy. The focus is on the experience of Chinese women--either what they endured under Mao&apos;s China or their lives as immigrants to Canada and the United States. They all share a feminist theme as the characters struggle in the face of gender discrimination in China and navigating relationships with men and their families. And of course, the loneliness of being in a new place without those you love and what it takes to </span>
  <span id="freeText9136876604242912942" style="display:none">Butterfly Tears is a lovely collection of short stories by Canadian author, Zoe Roy. The focus is on the experience of Chinese women--either what they endured under Mao's China or their lives as immigrants to Canada and the United States. They all share a feminist theme as the characters struggle in the face of gender discrimination in China and navigating relationships with men and their families. And of course, the loneliness of being in a new place without those you love and what it takes to build a new life.<br /><br />I really enjoyed this book and was able to read it in a couple of days. I particularly liked the haunting introduction in the first story, Butterfly Tears, and the charming twist in Life Insurance. And overall, there is a nice sense of setting and voice. <br /><br />Thank you so much to the author for offering me a copy of this book in exchange for a review.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9136876604242912942" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

